  "why": "The paper does not demonstrate reuse of fault-inducing inputs discovered on one model to test other models, nor does it include explicit fuzzing design mechanisms aimed at discovering transferable attacks. The experiments focus on (1) fine-tuning the SUT with generated test cases to reduce its failures, and (2) fine-tuning one cross-referenced ASR so CrossASR++ (via improved cross-referencing) uncovers more failures for other SUTs. This is an improvement-of-evaluation and model-evolution study, not an evaluation of attack transferability where fault-inducing inputs found on a surrogate are directly replayed against unseen targets to show transfer.",
  "evidence": "Page 676, Section II.B Improving CrossASR++: \"To make the cross-referenced ASR systems able to evolve as well, we enable CrossASR++ to record both failed and successful test cases for these ASR systems inside it. ... it creates the test case database 2 that stores the test cases generated for cross-referenced ASR systems in each iteration. Then, it utilizes these test cases to fine-tune the cross-referenced ASR systems in the same way as we evolve an SUT.\"; Page 678, Section III.C Preliminary Evaluation (RQ2, Result): \"By fine-tuning one of the cross-referenced ASR systems using generated test cases, the number of failed test cases found by CrossASR++ in Wav2Vec, DeepSpeech2, Wav2letter, and Wit increases by 5.70%, 7.25%, 3.93% and 1.52%, respectively.\" — these passages show the paper improves cross-referencing through fine-tuning but do not show experiments that \"reuse fault-inducing inputs discovered on one model to test others,\" which is required to demonstrate cross-model attack transferability."
